<br>
24th December  2001<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.worldnuclear.org/backref/ba/01/01_ba25.htm">www.worldnuclear.org/backref/ba/01/01_ba25.htm</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
<br>
The first year of the new millennium may go down in history as the start of the ÅeNuclear RenaissanceÅf. While the last few months were dominated by fresh security concerns in the wake of the September 11th attacks, 2001 as a whole saw a run of  positive developments for the industry that was unprecedented in recent years.<br>
<br>
As in many areas, the US set the pace - beginning with a major energy supply ÅecrunchÅf in California. The California crisis led to massive media coverage of the prospects for a nuclear revival, with public endorsements from figures including George Bush and Alan Greenspan. As the year drew to a close, one industry commentator observed that, while no new units had yet been ordered in the US, the mood had changed so much that any failure to do so next year would be a story in its own right. Below, NucNetÅfs round-up of the nuclear ÅehappeningsÅf of 2001:<br>
<br>
January: The Åegood newsÅf began in the US with the publication of statistics showing that, for the first time in a decade, nuclear power had overtaken coal to boast the cheapest generating costs of any major electricity source. Shortly afterwards, leading economist Lester Thurow issued a public challenge to environmentalists world-wide to Ågadmit they were wrongÅh about nuclear power or face the consequences of continued opposition - in the form of accelerating climate change. His call was echoed at the World Economic Forum by EU energy commissioner Loyola de Palacio, who underlined the key role of nuclear power both in combating climate change and in securing energy supplies. In Switzerland, an independent study showed that proposals to phase out nuclear power could cost the country at least 40 billion euros.<br>
<br>
February: Still in Switzerland, the government published its proposals for a new federal atomic energy law, which rejected any set limits to the operating lifetimes of existing nuclear plants, but proposed ending spent fuel reprocessing. France and Germany signed an official agreement to resume return transports of vitrified radwaste from France to Germany, ending a lengthy political stalemate. The governor of JapanÅfs Fukushima prefecture held up plans for the countryÅfs first use of MOX fuel at Fukushima-1. On the business front, SpainÅfs Endesa and Iberdrola called off a Åemega-mergerÅf plan, and FranceÅfs EDF got the green light to take control of GermanyÅfs third largest power utility, EnBW.<br>
<br>
March: In the US, two leading IT executives Scott McNeally of Sun Microsystems and Craig Barrett of Intel said nuclear power was the Åeonly solutionÅf to CaliforniaÅfs energy crisis. Vice-president Dick Cheney also went on national TV to say the time had come to Åere-examine the benefitsÅf of nuclear. In Europe, Finnish prime minister Paavo Lipponen described moves by some western countries to forego the nuclear option as Åeeconomically absurdÅf. And the US nuclear industry helped its own case by producing record performance figures for the second year in a row. However, the Taiwanese industry cast itself in a less favourable light, thanks to a power failure incident at the Maanshan nuclear plant.<br>
<br>
April: European trade association Eurelectric issued a report blaming the California crisis on a Ågpoor fuel mix that places too much reliance on gas-fired plantÅh. It confidently assured readers that a similar crisis Ågcould not happenÅh in Europe. The US Enrichment Corporation said the 20-year Åemegatonnes to megawattsÅf deal with Russia was 40% ahead of schedule. British EnergyÅfs Canadian subsidiary, Bruce Power, said it expected to restart units 3 and 4 of the Bruce A nuclear plant by mid-2003. And BNFL said spent fuel shipments from Germany to Sellafield would resume shortly, ending a ÅemoratoriumÅf that had lasted almost three years. <br>
<br>
May: President Bush unveiled a long-awaited national energy policy report, and confirmed that the US now aimed to ÅeexpandÅf the use of nuclear power. A few days later, his vice-president, Dick Cheney, stressed the key role of nuclear in national energy policy in a key-note speech to the Nuclear Energy InstituteÅfs annual congress. At the same meeting, a leading investment banker said that new US nuclear plants were now Ågnot only a wishÅc but a necessityÅh. Still in the US, the Yucca Mountain spent fuel repository project got a strong boost from four new scientific studies by the Department of Energy (DOE). And, in Finland, parliament ratified the governmentÅfs decision last year to construct a spent fuel repository at Olkiluoto. However, the month ended on a ÅedownÅf note in Japan, where voters in the village of Kariwa voted against allowing the use of MOX fuel in the Kashiwazaki Kariwa nuclear plant.<br>
<br>
June: President Vladimir Putin signed legislation that paves the way for Russia to import spent fuel from abroad for storage and reprocessing. GermanyÅfs political leaders and main power companies signed an agreement to limit the operating lifetimes of existing nuclear power plants. As if on cue, a key EU advisory group said it was ÅedifficultÅf to see how Europe could both tackle climate change and ensure energy supplies at reasonable prices without the continued use of nuclear. And a minister in ItalyÅfs new government said Italy may re-think its decision to abandon the use of nuclear power. In France, a new epidemiological study reinforced the growing scientific consensus that leukaemia ÅeclustersÅf around major industrial facilities are probably the result of rapid Åepopulation mixingÅf in previously isolated areas. And British Energy CEO Peter Hollins stepped down, to be replaced ad interim by incoming chairman Robin Jeffrey.<br>
<br>
July: The European Commission officially published the findings of a major research study (ExternE), which confirmed that the external costs of nuclear power are far lower than those for fossil fuels, and about the same as hydro. EU energy commissioner Loyola de Palacio said any move to phase out nuclear without explaining the corresponding loss in benefits would be ÅeirresponsibleÅf. However, environment ministers at the COP6 talks approved an agreement that appeared to specifically exclude nuclear from the list of ÅepermissibleÅf technologies for combating climate change. GermanyÅfs Green environment minister, Jurgen Trittin, also decided he knew better than the Czech regulatory authorities, and called for the immediate closure of Temelin.<br>
<br>
August: One of GermanyÅfs leading power company executives, Walter Hohlefelder of Eon, told a meeting in Switzerland that a nuclear renaissance in Europe including in Germany was now a distinct possibility. As US nuclear operator Entergy announced a deal to buy the Vermont Yankee plant for nearly four times its original offer, a detailed new study by NAC Worldwide Consultants demonstrated dramatically the extent to which nuclear plant purchase prices have escalated since the first such deal just three years ago. In Sweden, Vattenfall wrote an open letter to the finance ministry, revealing that the countryÅfs ÅeuniqueÅf nuclear power generation tax now accounted for some 15% of its total nuclear generation costs, including capital financing.<br>
<br>
September: The month started on a Åehigh noteÅf, with the heads of BritainÅfs two main nuclear companies BNFL and British Energy  saying they were now actively exploring plans to build a new generation of British nuclear plants. In France, the Areva Group was officially launched, bringing together three of the countryÅfs main nuclear organisations. The other main French player, EDF, got the green light for an indirect take-over of SpainÅfs Hidrocantabrico effectively giving it a foothold in the relatively-isolated Spanish electricity market. In the Netherlands, a court blocked a second attempt to force the early closure of the Borssele nuclear plant. However in common with much of the world the industry was hit by new security concerns in the wake of 11th September. The US Nuclear Regulatory Commission immediately advised all nuclear plants to go to the highest level of security, and similar steps were taken in other countries. The IAEA director-general, Mohamed ElBaradei, described the US attacks as Åga wake-up call to us allÅh and the IAEA general conference in Vienna announced immediate steps to reinforce nuclear security world-wide.<br>
<br>
October: US energy secretary Spencer Abraham said 11th September had brought Americans Ågface to face with our energy historyÅh, and vowed that ensuring security of supply would now be his number one policy priority. A public opinion poll carried out one month after the attacks found that a record number of Americans favoured the use of nuclear energy, and considered nuclear power plants safe. In Belgium, the government said it would push through a (previously-announced) bill limiting nuclear plant operating lifetimes to 40 years. GermanyÅfs environment minister ordered a review of Åequality managementÅf procedures at all nuclear power plants, in the wake of a level 2 coolant system incident at Philippsburg-2. The UK government gave BNFL the go-ahead to start full-scale commercial production of MOX fuel. And USEC said it was ready to Åemove forwardÅf with the development of advanced US centrifuge technology.<br>
<br>
November: The South African-led international consortium aiming to build a full-scale demonstration pebble bed modular reactor re-affirmed support for the project following a feasibility study, but said a construction decision had been delayed by up to 12 months.  CanadaÅfs Nuclear Safety Commission gave the provisional go-ahead for the restart of Ontario Power GenerationÅfs four-unit Pickering A station. The European Parliament debated last yearÅfs Green Paper on security of supply and approved a resolution underlining the need to keep nuclear power at the heart of EuropeÅfs energy mix. The US House of Representatives voted to  renew the Price-Anderson Act legislation that provides the framework for the US nuclear liability system. The British government announced plans for a new civil nuclear Liabilities Management Authority. The European Bank for Reconstruction and Development postponed indefinitely a decision to approve a loan for completion of UkraineÅfs Khmelnitski-2 and Rovno-4 (K2-R4) nuclear units, following last-minute objections to the conditions. And Austria and the Czech Republic ended a year-long ÅedialogueÅf over the Temelin nuclear plant, with Austria pledging to Åecontribute constructivelyÅf to the energy-related part of Czech EU membership talks.<br>
<br>
December: In Sweden, the municipality of Osthammar became the first to formally accept site investigations aimed at determining the suitability of the site as a potential location for a national spent fuel final repository. BrazilÅfs national council for energy policy (CNPE) gave the go-ahead for a study that could lead to completion of a third unit at the Angra nuclear power plant site. Framatome ANP announced the resignation of its president and CEO, Dominique Vignon, and his replacement by senior Cogema executive Vincent Maurel. The US Department of Commerce issued its final ruling in the USEC-brought trade case against Urenco and Eurodif over European imports to the US of low-enriched uranium. BNFL celebrated Christmas by beginning plutonium commission at its new MOX plant, after the safety authorities gave the final go-ahead. And the year ended with a birthday party, as 20th December marked the 50th anniversary of the first-ever production of useable amounts of nuclear electricity, at the US Experimental Breeder Reactor 1 (EBR-1). <p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
